# Commit Message Format

## Format

`<type> Imperative summary` — first line under ~72 chars.

Optional body: blank line, then details if the commit warrants explanation.

## Workflow

1. Run `git diff --staged` (or `git status` if nothing staged) to infer changes.
2. Pick the single best-matching tag from the table below.
3. Write the message in imperative mood ("Add" not "Added", "Fix" not "Fixed").

## Tags

| Tag | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `feature` | New behavior, capability, or user-facing functionality |
| `bug-fix` | Correcting incorrect behavior or regressions |
| `docs` | Documentation-only changes |
| `refactor` | Code restructure without behavior change |
| `test` | Adding or improving tests |
| `chore` | Maintenance (tooling, configs, housekeeping) |

## Examples

- `<feature> Add configurable reward shaping for jump landing`
- `<bug-fix> Correct foot contact detection on uneven terrain`
- `<docs> Document training flags for full-state observations`
- `<refactor> Simplify action clipping logic in legged robot`
- `<test> Add regression test for observation normalization`
- `<chore> Update pre-commit hooks for lint consistency`

## Validation

Before finalizing, verify:
- Message starts with `<type> `.
- `type` is one of: `feature`, `bug-fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`.
- No colon after the tag (`<type> Message`, not `<type>: Message`).
- Summary is clear and specific to the change intent.
